          "body": "Proverbs 9:10 — 'The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom, and the knowledge of the Holy One is understanding' — is the theological summit of the entire ten-chapter prologue and one of the most cited verses in the Old Testament's wisdom corpus. The word translated 'beginning' (techillah) means starting point, first principle, the root from which everything else grows. This is not wisdom's introductory level; it is wisdom's generative source. Every proverb in chapters 10-31 is a branch of this root. Proverbs 1:7 stated the same thesis at the book's opening; 9:10 restates it at the prologue's close, forming an inclusio that frames the entire pedagogical program. The second line is equally important: 'knowledge of the Holy One is understanding.' The Hebrew for 'Holy One' (qadosh) is plural of majesty — possibly trinitarian in implication, certainly an intensification pointing to the absolute moral otherness of God. Understanding (binah) is not the product of accumulated learning; it is the result of *knowing* this God personally. Calvin's comment on this verse is apt: wisdom does not begin with syllogisms; it begins with the trembling acknowledgment that the God who made you has the right to instruct you."
